00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.060
Hey everyone, welcome to Talk Python.

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:47.880
I'm really excited to have you here to talk about this pretty important topic of funding

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:52.080
open source infrastructure and some of the things that are actually the underpinnings

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:53.980
of the Python ecosystem itself.

00:02:53.980 --> 00:02:54.900
So welcome.

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:57.680
Let's get started with a quick introduction.

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:02.160
Got four of you on the show this week and that is really excellent.

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:03.940
I think it's going to give us a lot of perspectives.

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:06.720
So I'd like to start with what's your background?

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:13.260
Why are you particularly passionate or interested in Python's open source infrastructure in particular?

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:14.600
And Carol, let's start with you.

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:15.900
Hi, thanks, Michael.

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:17.280
I am Carol Willing.

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:23.820
I am a director of the Python Software Foundation and also a core developer on Project Jupyter at Cal Poly.

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:28.940
I have a background in econometrics and economics as well as engineering.

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:36.920
And I really care about the infrastructure because it supports so much of what we do in education,

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:43.440
whether at the university level or on the K through 12 level in the states as well as globally.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:44.180
Yeah, excellent.

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:45.640
It's super important education.

00:03:45.920 --> 00:03:57.380
I think one of the great growth areas of Python and a lot of interesting new projects and people are coming into it is coming from academics and from the data science space.

00:03:57.380 --> 00:03:59.360
And so that's right, right in there.

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:00.540
Eva, how about you?

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:02.720
My name is Eva Jalowska.

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:05.980
I am the director of operations at the Python Software Foundation.

00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:12.540
Even though I do have a little bit of technical experience, all of my Python involvement has been community related.

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:19.020
I did get involved with the PSF as a third party meeting planner working on PyCon.

00:04:19.020 --> 00:04:21.160
And that started in 2008.

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:28.220
In 2011, I did a career shift and joined the PSF exclusively to work on PyCon and other foundation activities.

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:31.680
In mid-2015, we began to hire additional staff.

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:34.340
And at that time, my role evolved to director of operations.

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:41.100
And even though PyCon is still a responsibility of mine, I now concentrate more on managing our staff and foundation sustainability,

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:48.680
which includes everything from how we internally operate to how we can best serve the Python community.

00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:52.600
And that is why Python infrastructure is important to me.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:53.500
All right.

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:53.860
Excellent.

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:55.920
Eric, how about you?

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:56.360
Yeah.

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:57.320
So I'm Eric Holscher.

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.980
And folks on this podcast probably know me most from kind of the work I do around read the docs.

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:10.980
And so I think, you know, both Donald with PyPI and myself are in a very similar position where we're running kind of large infrastructure.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:16.200
infrastructure projects that don't have or they don't necessarily feel like they have the largest amount of community support.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:21.320
And I think we're trying to kind of raise awareness around how that might be an issue going forward.

00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:27.660
And so there's definitely kind of a selfish motive for kind of having my own work be funded better and more supported,

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:33.680
as well as kind of being able to build things like this within the community and kind of setting examples of models.

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:40.640
So if people want to build more infrastructure to support the community, there is actually a model for making that sustainable so more of it can happen.

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:43.140
I think that's kind of my angle on it.

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:43.500
Yeah.

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:43.820
Okay.

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:44.380
Great.

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:44.720
Thanks.

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:51.180
And Donald, you were on episode 64 and you shared a lot of the work that you've been doing with PyPI.

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:54.440
But go ahead and tell everyone about yourself for this episode.

00:05:54.440 --> 00:05:54.800
Yeah.

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:55.900
So I'm Donald Stuff.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:06:05.220
And, you know, I work on PyPI and pip and sort of Disutils, the sort of related projects for Python's packaging story.

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:14.560
In that regard, I run operations for PyPI and I'm sort of the primary developer and operations on both PyPI and pip.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.400
There are other people who will help out.

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:26.100
But as I was currently being paid my time for that and that enabled me to spend a lot more time than other people were able to.

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:35.780
I suppose it sends a little bit of a mixed message about whether the project needs help if there's somebody whose full-time job is to work on an open source project, right?

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:36.800
Like PyPI.

00:06:36.800 --> 00:06:37.920
What do you think?

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:39.840
It's sort of a dangerous place to be in.

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:43.200
I mean, full transparency, I was just laid off from my job.

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:46.700
So I am no longer employed full-time to do that.

00:06:47.380 --> 00:07:02.180
And it's dangerous because now that I'm laid off, all of a sudden we just lost the only full-time employee working on that project, which is a huge loss of hours available to dedicate to different resources in that space.

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:02.580
Yeah.

00:07:02.580 --> 00:07:13.380
And that whole experience, you talked about it on Twitter and saying it was not like HP decided they were going to defund PyPI or anything like that.

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:15.720
It was just, you know, HP is going through some challenges.

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:24.280
They laid off a bunch of people and it just so happened they, I guess, felt like this funding for PyPI didn't really match with what they were doing anymore.

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:29.340
And I want to be really clear to everyone listening that this is not to throw HP under the bus, right?

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:33.940
Like HP was doing more than any other company out there to fund PyPI.

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:41.500
The fact that they, like, stepped back to being on par with the other companies is unfortunate, but it's not like we should be unhappy with HP.

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:43.360
It's more like, well, wait a minute.

00:07:43.360 --> 00:07:55.500
Why did we have just this one company that happened to, like, more or less donate an employee to run the most important way that libraries are shared in Python, right?

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:55.900
Yeah.

00:07:55.900 --> 00:08:01.320
And, you know, as far as I can tell, they actually didn't even know they were defunding PyPI.

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:01.480
Yeah.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:07.280
You know, this is a fairly large scale layoff and my entire team got dissolved.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:18.600
So as far as I've been told, you know, I just got caught in a large net and there was no sort of knowledge that PyPI was even a thing at the level that this was being taken place of.

00:08:18.780 --> 00:08:19.500
Yeah, absolutely.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:28.600
So I, you know, you and I spoke for an hour on episode 64 about Python packaging and what PyPI is, among many other things.

00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:34.340
But let's start this conversation by kind of laying out the elements that are in play here.

00:08:34.340 --> 00:08:36.900
So, Eric, you talked about read the docs.

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:39.220
We've talked about PyPI.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:46.740
But, Eric, what other stuff do you think is under this banner of open source infrastructure and the Python ecosystem?

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:48.980
I mean, I think those are the two big projects.

00:08:48.980 --> 00:08:55.240
I think also kind of the Conda ecosystem around scientific Python is another place.

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:58.660
I think a lot of it is, at this point, kind of companies.

00:08:58.660 --> 00:09:05.640
So things like, you know, Travis CI is a huge point where a lot of the open source infrastructure is built on that.

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:08.660
And they've actually been building a sustainable business around that.

00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:15.840
But I think if, you know, if Travis CI went away tomorrow, that would have huge impacts on kind of the Python developer ecosystem.

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:24.060
Yeah, and really just kind of all that entire kind of suite of developer tools that people are kind of using on their day to day.

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:30.840
And, yeah, but I think in terms of kind of Python specifically, I think, you know, pip and, you know, PyPI are the most obvious.

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:34.960
And I think read the docs and other just tools that developers are using.

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:39.120
And, you know, maybe someone else will have a better kind of more encompassing answer.

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:48.620
I think, you know, in some regards, kind of Twitter and GitHub, right, are also both in that basket where we have these massive corporations running these for us for free.

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:50.780
And that's very much infrastructure we depend on.

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:55.240
But, you know, that's a little bit less precarious because they are building kind of businesses around them.

00:09:55.500 --> 00:10:03.960
But there are some other issues with that, for sure, as you see, maybe with something like NPM being the kind of most analogous to PyPI.

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:04.660
Right.

00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:08.220
Yeah, and NPM does apply to Python developers.

00:10:08.220 --> 00:10:18.500
There's a lot of tools that you get from NPM as well as anytime we're building web frameworks, we probably want to go get some JavaScript stuff as well just for the front end work.

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:31.320
You know, I think, first of all, one of the things I would like to discuss or sort of point out that you guys might not, people who are listening might not realize, is the scale of the cost of some of these projects.

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:36.780
So for PyPI, Donald, obviously, you were being employed to work on it and there's your time.

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:39.780
But there's also actual infrastructure expenses.

00:10:39.780 --> 00:10:44.800
And luckily, from what I understand, those are still being covered by places like Rackspace and so on.

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:58.440
But for PyPI, you said last May we had 340 terabytes of traffic and that was roughly $35,000 a month in infrastructure expenses, right?

00:10:58.440 --> 00:10:59.200
Yeah.

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:06.040
Yeah, so we've now gotten to the point where I believe the last 30 days we've hit 390 terabytes of bandwidth.

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:14.160
So we're starting to push closer to $40,000 a month in donated services.

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:16.700
That's what the cost would be if we actually paid for that.

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:20.500
We are very lucky that we have a Fastly Rackspace Dream host.

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:21.800
I can't list them all.

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:27.340
But there's eight or ten different companies that donate those services to us.

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:31.240
But yeah, it's a significant cost without those donations.

00:11:31.240 --> 00:11:34.040
We would not be able to bear the cost of doing that.

00:11:34.040 --> 00:11:34.380
Yeah.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:42.360
Even a very happy donor couldn't – very unlikely that they could handle that much of an expense on a monthly basis.

00:11:42.620 --> 00:11:46.500
Eva, what do you think about funding some of these projects?

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:49.340
Like where's the current funding coming from?

00:11:49.340 --> 00:11:58.320
You know, Donald talked a little bit about HP and the guys donating at Rackspace, donating bandwidth and to the other companies as well.

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:00.860
But where else does funding come from?

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:07.460
So most of it, as already everyone mentioned, is through in-kind sponsorship.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:14.780
So everything from server providers, CDN management providers, search optimizers, et cetera, even to design work.

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:17.280
For instance, if you look – I know that Donald said he couldn't list all of them.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:24.440
But if you look at the bottom of pypi.org, you can see all the logos of the donated services that Donald has received.

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:28.800
Obviously, the main one has been HP employing Donald.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:32.900
And we also make up a lot of that through volunteer time.

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:38.060
We have a lot of volunteers that work and put a lot of time into making it happen.

00:12:38.060 --> 00:12:44.120
And up to March of this year, the PSF infrastructure was completely managed by volunteers.

00:12:44.120 --> 00:12:51.860
And then in March, we decided to hire an IT manager who is slowly gaining his bearings around the ecosystem.

00:12:51.860 --> 00:12:54.500
The PSF does fund a little bit.

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:59.260
We do, for instance, maintain domains and things like that and other random charges.

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:01.800
Sometimes it happens for certificates or things like that.

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:10.720
But we do have, for instance, other – and I wanted to kind of go back a little bit because there are a lot more infrastructure than just dev tools, in my opinion,

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:18.020
especially since we do a lot of the day-to-day foundation stuff like mail.python.org or even our wiki.

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:20.880
That's, I guess, more internally used.

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:22.420
But I have an example.

00:13:22.420 --> 00:13:27.940
For instance, for mail.python.org, last year, the server went belly up.

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:32.760
And this was before we had our IT manager.

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:45.620
And when you're in peak PyCon sponsorship sign-up time and you don't have mail for four days, that could be a very extreme thing.

00:13:45.620 --> 00:13:48.940
So it actually took us four days, including the weekend, to be able to restore it.

00:13:49.060 --> 00:13:55.000
And we had to search down volunteers who were no longer active and that had – we had to find who had backups.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:00.820
But I can't help to wonder, like, what if those volunteers weren't available that weekend?

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:02.160
What would we have done?

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:07.900
So it's kind of questions like that that makes us really think, how can we improve the funding?

00:14:09.100 --> 00:14:16.820
Yeah, so there's the keeping the organization running, and then there's the public-facing stuff like PyPI and read the docs.

00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:17.820
Yeah.

00:14:17.820 --> 00:14:18.440
Yeah.

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:20.920
Any other funding, Carol, that you can think of?

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:23.040
Other things that we should maybe throw under this?

00:14:23.040 --> 00:14:26.280
What is open source infrastructure for the Python community?

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:44.160
Yeah, I think that there's key infrastructure that, you know, have a fixed cost that, you know, a lot of our sponsors have very generously given us time or services in order to have even the base technology to run things on.

00:14:44.160 --> 00:15:11.800
And then if you look at the team that's in place from an infrastructure standpoint for just running the Python Software Foundation, it's like a hugely leaned startup with Eva and her crew running a 24-7 global organization pushing around terabytes of data and with volunteers largely being the staff that gets things done.

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:28.020
And, you know, my concern is to be able to sustain the fixed costs of the infrastructure over time, but also be able to have some variable resources that are funded so that we're not burning out volunteers.

00:15:28.020 --> 00:15:38.580
I mean, Donald was very generously funded by HP, but his time and effort went far beyond just his salary for the day.

00:15:38.580 --> 00:15:42.820
And, you know, we all owe him a huge thank you for that.

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:45.100
And the same with Eric on Read the Docs.

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:57.140
It's a labor of love as well as a key part of our infrastructure, as is PyVideo.org, our user groups, being able to fund scholarships for us to grow the community.

00:15:57.140 --> 00:16:02.000
So I think infrastructure really sort of touches everything that we do.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.240
Yeah, that's a really interesting view.

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:10.520
I just interviewed Paul Logsdon from PyVideo, and that's coming out of the week of this one being recorded.

00:16:10.720 --> 00:16:13.500
So that's a really interesting one as well.

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:17.700
Eric, can you speak to Read the Docs a little bit?

00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:20.520
And how, you know, what's the expenses?

00:16:20.520 --> 00:16:22.040
How do you guys keep that running there?

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:22.980
Sure.

00:16:22.980 --> 00:16:23.560
Yeah.

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:33.260
And just to kind of follow on quickly with Carol's point, I think, yeah, like the staff of PyCon as well is just this amazing, like this unreasonable, amazing outpouring of love from the community.

00:16:33.260 --> 00:16:39.420
And all of that staff is volunteer, except for, you know, a few people at the top, but the hours that go into running events like that.

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:41.800
I mean, I have my own conference night, I know.

00:16:41.800 --> 00:16:45.420
So, yeah, there's so much work that we all depend on as a community.

00:16:45.420 --> 00:16:50.120
But, yeah, so anyway, the costs of Read the Docs, similarly, are paid for by Rackspace.

00:16:50.700 --> 00:16:59.000
I think Rackspace is like one of these people where if their sponsorship of open source and the Python community as well went away, these massive things.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:03.000
I know, like the cryptography project that's doing a bunch of really good crypto stuff.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:11.660
I mean, there's so many backbone kind of CI tools and servers and all these costs of all of the projects around the Python ecosystem that Rackspace is putting the bill for.

00:17:12.080 --> 00:17:16.820
And if that ever went away, there would be a huge kind of scramble, I think.

00:17:16.820 --> 00:17:20.680
And that's another just huge piece of infrastructure, all these servers, everything's running on.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:24.780
Our recent bill from Rackspace was, I believe, $3,600.

00:17:24.780 --> 00:17:30.020
So we keep our server costs incredibly low for the amount of things that we're doing.

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:32.380
I think we do about 25 million page views.

00:17:32.380 --> 00:17:36.340
I think we push close to 10 terabytes of data.

00:17:36.820 --> 00:17:38.740
But mostly we're serving static files.

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:48.980
So we have a very kind of low cost of infrastructure based on the – and a lot of that was architectural decisions that we made because we knew the funding environment that we were existing within.

00:17:48.980 --> 00:17:50.760
So everything is very lean.

00:17:50.760 --> 00:17:54.000
Yeah, similarly, the main cost is people.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:05.080
Operations person who's wearing a pager to make sure the Python community's documentation goes down has a market rate of easily $100,000 a year, at least within the U.S. kind of pay scales.

00:18:05.080 --> 00:18:11.940
And so that dwarfs the, what, $40,000 to $50,000 that we would pay in pure infrastructure costs.

00:18:11.940 --> 00:18:17.620
But that said, if Rackspace did go away, that would be a huge – there would be a huge scramble for us to kind of cover that cost.

00:18:17.620 --> 00:18:18.020
Yeah.

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:25.100
You mentioned GitHub, and if it went away, there would definitely be terrible disturbance in the forest sort of feeling.

00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:30.000
Are there contingency plans for if Rackspace backed up?

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:35.020
Because, you know, this is the common theme, and thank you so much, Rackspace, for being such a supporter, right?

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:38.460
But it's also becoming like a single point of failure.

00:18:38.460 --> 00:18:40.020
Do you guys know what you would do?

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:41.720
We've had a few different people offer.

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:46.620
I mean, I think, honestly, the initial step would probably be to stop doing builds.

00:18:47.600 --> 00:18:55.840
Because a lot of the cost of servers is the build infrastructure, and if we just stuck, you know, static files up somewhere, that would be a viable alternative for at least like a week or something.

00:18:55.840 --> 00:19:04.820
And, you know, like somebody maybe couldn't release a new library, but the 99% case is still kind of, you know, the old documentation that we host for everyone would still be available.

00:19:04.820 --> 00:19:08.560
And I'm sure we could find yet another, you know, donated service.

00:19:08.780 --> 00:19:21.140
But kind of the plan B was so scary for so long that it kind of really did spur us to start looking into business models and kind of sustainability on our own, because that was kind of a scary outcome, right?

00:19:21.140 --> 00:19:30.760
And I think similar to having one company employ someone to work primarily on a project, I think having one company hosting all of the infrastructure for free, right?

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:34.260
Like it builds this kind of all the eggs in one basket scenario.

00:19:34.260 --> 00:19:43.440
And I think there's, like I'd never even really considered Rackspace in that light, but I think if we really took a deep look at our community, we would find we have a lot of our eggs in a very small number of baskets.

00:19:43.440 --> 00:19:56.440
And, you know, I think Russ Keith McGee, who's one of the really people that I've been watching talk about this for a while, says, you know, we really need like kind of that diversity in funding and support to really have something that's truly sustainable.

00:19:56.720 --> 00:20:10.240
And so I think that that's definitely the path we need to look down is, you know, how do we reduce dependence on these small set of very generous companies and towards something that's more kind of inclusive of the entire community, supporting the entire community?

00:20:10.240 --> 00:20:11.400
Yeah, I agree.

00:20:11.400 --> 00:20:20.040
I think it's really a positive thing that you guys have write the docs and all the stuff that's starting to take shape as a business there.

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:25.680
Do you want to spend just a moment and tell people about what you're doing to make that a little more sustainable?

00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:31.300
Yeah, so we actually, we turned, we built like an official kind of business around Read the Docs two years ago.

00:20:31.300 --> 00:20:46.640
The conferences are actually a completely separate endeavor that just kind of are connected through me as a human, which is also its own business, which is also, you know, building into a sustainable, you know, we have, we're going to have similar to Python, have kind of a part time to start operations person.

00:20:47.180 --> 00:20:54.460
But with Read the Docs, we basically tried a bunch of different models that everyone's talked about, you know, consulting, support contracts, all this stuff.

00:20:54.960 --> 00:21:09.640
And it turns out that kind of like, unlike a database or an operating system, documentation is not mission critical enough within most organizations for them to pay for support contracts, or training or these things, you know, where we're kind of very much a second thought in a lot of development organizations.

00:21:10.040 --> 00:21:16.160
And so I think that's been really hampering our ability to use some of the more traditional business models that have worked in open source.

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:25.940
And so we basically fell back on advertising, which is, you know, kind of the one true business model on the internet that works for paid or for free sites, right?

00:21:25.940 --> 00:21:37.380
Like every large free website on the internet, especially, you know, if you view Read the Docs as a content publisher, which at the end of the day, we really are, you know, we're very similar to, you know, a newspaper in those terms, right?

00:21:37.380 --> 00:21:39.460
Advertising is the model, right?

00:21:39.460 --> 00:21:44.600
Like everyone that's reading documentation on Read the Docs is never going to pay us money, even one penny, right?

00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:56.240
Like there's so many more readers to writers or maintainers that the only way to kind of manifest value from those very small interactions is to put an ad on it and to have someone pay you for that small amount of attention.

00:21:56.240 --> 00:22:02.160
And so we basically set out to build a advertising business model that we are proud of.

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:03.560
And so we're not tracking our users.

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:04.720
We're doing one ad per page.

00:22:04.720 --> 00:22:07.780
It's kind of at the bottom of the sidebar, so it's not in your way.

00:22:07.780 --> 00:22:13.740
And so we're really trying to kind of build a model that respects users and kind of respects advertisers and can be a win-win.

00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:20.000
And so we call it kind of newspaper advertising on the internet, just because it's like, you know, we put a, we know people are here.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:21.300
We're going to put an image on a page.

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:24.380
Some people are going to look at it and they're going to click it and you're going to pay us for that privilege.

00:22:24.380 --> 00:22:28.860
And so we're really trying to kind of build an ad product that we can be proud of.

00:22:28.860 --> 00:22:34.220
I think it's really interesting and it's worth talking about because the other business models are really hard.

00:22:34.220 --> 00:22:45.000
like how could you possibly ask somebody to like say as a publisher on there to say to pay at least the people who are doing free open source work,

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:53.740
basically as a volunteer on their own project, like having them pay to use the site is like insult to injury because they're trying to write docs for the community for free.

00:22:53.880 --> 00:22:55.200
And you're like, well, you got to pay to do that.

00:22:55.200 --> 00:23:03.240
You're like, so a lot of the models, like you said, are, are challenging, but luckily both PyPI and read the docs have a tremendous amount of traffic.

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:08.180
So there's a possibility that some kind of ad story does make sense.

00:23:08.180 --> 00:23:10.000
Carol, what do you think?

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.800
What do you got some ideas around this ad stuff?

00:23:12.800 --> 00:23:13.240
Wow.

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:18.940
You know, I think ads probably have a whole range of people's viewpoints on them.

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:31.020
I think I know when read the docs kind of went to the ad model, we had some people that were really for it and some people that were sort of questioning, like, I don't know that I want ads in my documentation.

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:42.080
Personally, like we worked through on the Jupyter project that the ads were subtle enough that we felt like sustaining the ecosystem of read the docs.

00:23:42.080 --> 00:23:53.960
And I'm, you know, I spend a lot of time writing documentation as a developer because I think it's so important and critical for onboarding people and for developers to build their skills.

00:23:54.400 --> 00:24:03.500
So, you know, I think advertising, it will get you some of the way and obviously all the things that we've done to date were here.

00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:15.480
These things are functioning, but oftentimes it feels like you're holding it together with like scotch tape and a lot of goodwill and ongoing goodwill from the sponsors that we have.

00:24:15.700 --> 00:24:26.320
So the question is really, in my view, how do you, you know, we're sort of facing like a classic problem in economics where who funds the infrastructure?

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:34.560
Like in a country, the infrastructure like roads, law enforcement, hospitals are largely funded by the government.

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:38.320
And so we're not directly paying for everything.

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:42.440
And I think we see similar things in open source.

00:24:42.720 --> 00:24:50.080
Many people benefit from, let's say, PyPI, for example, whether or not they contribute to it.

00:24:50.080 --> 00:24:59.380
And so you've got like that classic economics, free riders getting the benefit, but not contributing anything to receive the benefit.

00:24:59.380 --> 00:25:03.540
And I'm not sure how you necessarily get that.

00:25:03.540 --> 00:25:04.040
Right.

00:25:04.040 --> 00:25:07.800
It's so challenging to take it back to like your country analogy.

00:25:08.580 --> 00:25:13.040
One of the ways countries deal with that is they come up with toll roads, right?

00:25:13.040 --> 00:25:15.100
Or toll bridges or things like that.

00:25:15.100 --> 00:25:16.280
And.

00:25:16.280 --> 00:25:16.980
Absolutely.

00:25:16.980 --> 00:25:17.980
Those.

00:25:17.980 --> 00:25:21.360
I personally find all of those things very distasteful.

00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:22.140
I don't like.

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:28.100
I used to live in New Jersey and I felt like I would drive like five miles and stop and pay a dime, drive six miles, pay a quarter.

00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:31.100
And I was just always at traffic jams paying like such a small.

00:25:31.100 --> 00:25:37.820
Like, why couldn't we just add a little bit of a gas tax or something like this that sort of solved the problem instead of trying.

00:25:37.820 --> 00:25:39.720
This thing is costing too much.

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:42.380
So we're going to patch a little fee onto it or something.

00:25:42.380 --> 00:25:44.680
And I feel like there's some analogies here as well.

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:45.120
Yeah.

00:25:45.120 --> 00:25:50.060
I also grew up in New Jersey and I can remember having to pay to actually go to the beach.

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:52.940
You know, you need a little badge on some of the beaches.

00:25:52.940 --> 00:26:00.680
You'd have to pay five, ten bucks, whatever it was to actually step foot on the beach, which on the West Coast we think is sort of very strange.

00:26:00.680 --> 00:26:01.600
It's very strange.

00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:01.800
Yeah.

00:26:01.820 --> 00:26:07.160
But I think certainly paying for service is one model.

00:26:07.160 --> 00:26:15.360
But I think much like you, I think it's not something that necessarily is attractive to many people.

00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:20.000
It benefits those that have money to pay for it versus the general community.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.900
And like you said, it's an annoyance.

00:26:22.900 --> 00:26:28.660
So I think there's got to be other nonprofit models that might be better suited.

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:33.360
And I won't profess to know the solution, but something different.

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:33.780
Yeah.

00:26:33.780 --> 00:26:39.160
We definitely don't want to bring some kind of model to this whole place that would kill the delight, right?

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:40.640
Kill the joy.

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:40.960
Absolutely.

00:26:40.960 --> 00:26:41.340
Yeah.

00:26:41.340 --> 00:26:42.700
Because that's something that's really special.

00:26:42.700 --> 00:26:46.220
Eva, how does the PSF pay for itself?

00:26:46.220 --> 00:26:49.220
The majority of the PSF's budget comes from PyCon.

00:26:49.220 --> 00:26:54.200
PyCon is our main expense and it's also our main source of revenue.

00:26:54.340 --> 00:27:03.100
My team and I work very hard every year to try to be in the positive after each PyCon, especially since it's so vital to the foundation's sustainability.

00:27:03.100 --> 00:27:13.440
That revenue helps us with future PyCon expenses as well as it helps the PSF have a budget for grants that we give out, which do help grow and strengthen the community.

00:27:13.440 --> 00:27:15.980
Some of these grants are infrastructure related.

00:27:15.980 --> 00:27:21.660
For example, the PSF has given financial support to read slash write the docs.

00:27:21.660 --> 00:27:29.860
And we recently even granted our Python packaging work group, which Donald and I are on, a grant to be used as needed.

00:27:30.100 --> 00:27:38.760
We want to be able to do more of it, but it is not sustainable for the PSF at the moment to fully support all of these projects.

00:27:38.760 --> 00:27:48.320
In addition to the importance of funding the infrastructure that the PSF oversees, we have other operations that need our financial attention.

00:27:48.320 --> 00:27:55.360
For example, the grants that the PSF disburses have been increasing approximately $65,000 year on year.

00:27:55.360 --> 00:28:00.660
So that is another important aspect I have to consider when planning the foundation's future.

00:28:00.660 --> 00:28:08.340
I mean, this is a little bit off topic, but if anyone's interested, I did cover this at PyGotham this year, so we can check it out for more details.

00:28:09.100 --> 00:28:19.620
We do have sponsorship support year on year from corporations, but surprisingly, that is a small percentage of where funds come from.

00:28:19.620 --> 00:28:27.200
We are hoping to continue to grow our staff, so we are internally working on how we can increase the foundation's corporate support.

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:37.580
My short-term goal is to improve our sponsorship perspectives, for example, by including some targeted traffic data from, let's say, PyPI to give to organizations.

