00:30:13.920 --> 00:30:20.380
Donald, have you considered any other models like what Read the Docs is doing or anything for PyPI?

00:30:20.380 --> 00:30:22.680
I mean, you do have a tremendous amount of traffic there.

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:25.720
Yeah, so I considered ads briefly.

00:30:25.720 --> 00:30:34.560
We didn't need them yet, so I kind of put it on the back burner because I do think people have sort of a – ads are polarizing.

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:38.100
And the less I get yelled at, the better.

00:30:39.460 --> 00:30:39.900
Yeah.

00:30:39.900 --> 00:30:49.760
But there are other things we've talked about, like the ability to host private packages on PyPI and pay for that privilege.

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:57.280
But then that starts to get into more questions like, well, if we start turning PyPI into sort of a business but still a nonprofit,

00:30:57.280 --> 00:31:02.620
are the sponsors that have been donating resources to us, how are they going to feel about that?

00:31:02.620 --> 00:31:08.460
Are we going to suddenly look at having to pay $40,000 a month if we start doing that?

00:31:08.740 --> 00:31:19.500
So it's sort of like walking a bit on a tightrope wanting to not do something that's going to make these people feel like they're investing or donating to a business.

00:31:19.500 --> 00:31:20.060
Yes.

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:23.260
While still being able to try to be more sustainable.

00:31:23.260 --> 00:31:25.080
That's a very careful balance.

00:31:25.080 --> 00:31:26.980
And I think it's tricky, right?

00:31:26.980 --> 00:31:29.560
And I don't want to make this conversation all about ads.

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:34.540
I don't necessarily think the solution is ads, but they're like an easy solution, right?

00:31:34.540 --> 00:31:35.640
You can easily throw them up.

00:31:35.640 --> 00:31:41.560
And as long as you control the site, like read the docs, for example, it's not hugely in the way for anybody.

00:31:41.560 --> 00:31:43.980
Michael, can I jump in with one comment on this?

00:31:43.980 --> 00:31:44.380
Yeah, please do.

00:31:44.380 --> 00:31:44.660
Go ahead.

00:31:44.660 --> 00:31:48.320
Sort of bridging what both Eva said and Donald said.

00:31:48.400 --> 00:32:00.800
I think one thing that we could do is perhaps leverage better instead of ads, but use the site to really honor and thank the sponsors.

00:32:01.460 --> 00:32:11.380
And to give the sponsors some greater visibility on the sites for actually taking the time and belief and effort to sponsor us.

00:32:11.380 --> 00:32:12.540
Yeah, that's a really good point.

00:32:12.540 --> 00:32:18.940
You know, maybe this is a good time we could sort of switch to trying to brainstorm about what can we do.

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:23.120
I mean, we've sort of been circling around that a little bit and what people have tried.

00:32:23.120 --> 00:32:25.060
Maybe what could or should we try?

00:32:25.060 --> 00:32:33.280
I think having the sponsors highlighted really clearly could easily make it more appealing to sponsor these projects, right?

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:38.600
Like if it was a small icon logo at the bottom of like the homepage, that's one thing.

00:32:38.600 --> 00:32:48.020
It's another if Rackspace gets to somehow be featured or Red Hat gets to somehow be featured in like a thing that is relevant to them, right?

00:32:48.660 --> 00:32:52.660
Maybe, for example, on the stuff to do with cloud computing.

00:32:52.660 --> 00:32:56.320
Red Hat gets a little, you know, like the packages to do with cloud computing.

00:32:56.320 --> 00:33:02.700
Maybe Red Hat gets some sort of visibility for, say, OpenStack and similarly for Rackspace.

00:33:02.700 --> 00:33:03.660
You know, something like that.

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:04.600
Eric, what do you think?

00:33:04.600 --> 00:33:06.700
So we actually have been thinking a lot about this.

00:33:06.700 --> 00:33:09.720
I mean, we don't do things quickly and without thought.

00:33:09.720 --> 00:33:17.280
And so one of the big things is we formed as a business and not a nonprofit because basically we do this as trying to prove a model.

00:33:17.540 --> 00:33:19.460
And so we don't want to constrain ourselves.

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:26.960
And so when we looked at doing a nonprofit and what they're allowed to do in terms of, you know, quote unquote sponsorship, you're basically allowed to do advertising.

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:30.580
But there can't be a call to action is at least the way that I understand it.

00:33:30.580 --> 00:33:32.460
So you see this, you know, similar.

00:33:32.460 --> 00:33:38.860
Django is doing this where they actually have a more visible thank you to their donors in the documentation.

00:33:39.400 --> 00:33:44.020
But it's very much a, you know, thank you, Red Hat for sponsoring or, you know, thank you, you know, whoever.

00:33:44.020 --> 00:33:48.700
They can't say, you know, come buy our new product for $10 off this month.

00:33:48.700 --> 00:33:50.680
And so that is the fundamental difference.

00:33:50.680 --> 00:33:50.900
Right.

00:33:50.960 --> 00:33:56.500
And so we thought as we try and kind of prove this model and really think through it, we didn't want those constraints.

00:33:56.880 --> 00:34:01.360
But some of the people we're talking to very much do just want that kind of more sponsorship model.

00:34:01.820 --> 00:34:11.780
And so really our goal in the long term is to build an ad business to the point where we're able to transition that with our existing sponsors to a more nonprofit sponsorship model.

00:34:11.780 --> 00:34:18.160
But really to start, we saw, you know, the Django Software Foundation did this and they are they have not hit their goal for the year.

00:34:18.160 --> 00:34:24.220
Just in a traditional kind of nonprofit donation model, even with a more visible thank you.

00:34:24.220 --> 00:34:28.340
Whereas Django REST framework actually has been successful with this model.

00:34:28.920 --> 00:34:32.220
And so, you know, there's there's a little bit of different conflicting views.

00:34:32.220 --> 00:34:38.860
But I think definitely kind of, you know, making the sponsors feel like they're getting something for their money is really the value.

00:34:38.860 --> 00:34:46.900
And so we went kind of purely for trying to build a model where we could actually give sponsors the most value possible.

00:34:46.900 --> 00:34:55.880
And then if we're successful in that and I can, you know, pay my rent each month, then we can start to impose more kind of strict regulations on what we're able to do.

00:34:56.020 --> 00:35:08.160
But by starting kind of as a nonprofit or as a for profit and allowing ourselves to kind of transition into a more kind of nonprofit style model, it gives us more flexibility to get it off the ground.

00:35:08.160 --> 00:35:11.500
That's an interesting point that you need the room to experiment.

00:35:11.500 --> 00:35:24.340
I think this is a pretty new space of trying to take a thing that was basically for free and turn it into a business, especially a thing that is free and people donated freely to it and turn it into a business.

00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:26.600
That's a real interesting challenge, right?

00:35:26.600 --> 00:35:27.420
And so I did.

00:35:27.420 --> 00:35:29.380
Actually, if I can add to that a little bit.

00:35:29.380 --> 00:35:30.560
Sorry to interrupt.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:31.380
Yeah, go ahead.

00:35:31.380 --> 00:35:46.180
So at the PSF, we actually do have maybe a different form of what we're discussing called success stories where we so this was developed in the redesign for the website, but it's not used as much as I would like it to be.

00:35:46.260 --> 00:36:00.400
So pretty much what we do is we say to our sponsors, especially top level sponsors, say, hey, why don't you write us a success story that we can post on our website of how Python has helped your organization grow or to where it is today?

00:36:00.600 --> 00:36:13.000
And I think that if we could maybe use that as a way to expose our sponsors more, I think it would not only please our sponsors, but it would please the community because it just wouldn't be like, hey, buy this product.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:13.460
Right.

00:36:13.460 --> 00:36:13.740
Okay.

00:36:13.740 --> 00:36:14.580
That's interesting.

00:36:14.580 --> 00:36:15.180
Yeah.

00:36:15.180 --> 00:36:25.400
People basically get to highlight how they're using Python in whatever area they're interested in, like whatever in their cloud computing platform, if they're a cloud provider or something like that, right?

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:25.960
Exactly.

00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:26.520
Yeah.

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:28.060
Eric, you were going to say something as well.

00:36:28.060 --> 00:36:36.220
Oh, yeah, I was just going to speak to Donald's point because I think it is super important that we did actually spin up a paid hosted model.

00:36:36.220 --> 00:36:38.440
And that is actually a separate entity.

00:36:38.440 --> 00:36:41.740
It's at readthedocs.com and it is a completely separate thing.

00:36:41.740 --> 00:36:47.840
And so that's kind of how we were hoping to address that balance between, you know, you're not paying to donate to a business.

00:36:47.840 --> 00:36:57.960
The advertising on readthedocs.org supports the readthedocs.org hosting and kind of costs, not hosting because Rackspace pays, but, you know, the cost of maintenance of that platform.

00:36:58.560 --> 00:37:00.480
And so you're not donating to a business, right?

00:37:00.480 --> 00:37:01.700
You're just allowing.

00:37:01.700 --> 00:37:05.160
It's one method that we're generating income to become sustainable.

00:37:05.160 --> 00:37:09.520
Not, you know, I'm not like lining my pockets, you know, with ad money or whatever.

00:37:09.520 --> 00:37:09.860
Right.

00:37:10.220 --> 00:37:12.120
And so that is something we thought a lot about.

00:37:12.120 --> 00:37:13.240
And we have provisions.

00:37:13.240 --> 00:37:15.660
We have different, you know, entities and all that kind of stuff.

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:18.580
That's something we are really, I think, is super important, right?

00:37:18.580 --> 00:37:24.360
You can't just be like, hey, we're going to start making money now and expect people to kind of, you know, donate to a business.

00:37:24.360 --> 00:37:26.200
It does have to be done kind of thoughtfully.

00:37:26.420 --> 00:37:27.980
Donald, your point was really interesting.

00:37:27.980 --> 00:37:32.140
And I think it touches on one angle of what I think is a very careful balance.

00:37:32.140 --> 00:37:39.960
Like, what if PyPI, let's say, went to some kind of business model that was, well, it looked like a business, like you said.

00:37:39.960 --> 00:37:41.980
And the business was doing okay.

00:37:41.980 --> 00:37:44.100
It was making $10,000 a month.

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:46.740
And then the people who donated to it said, you have a business.

00:37:46.740 --> 00:37:47.820
Why would we donate to you?

00:37:47.820 --> 00:37:50.080
We were pulling our $40,000 a month funding.

00:37:50.080 --> 00:37:54.940
You know, all of a sudden, you know, you've killed the golden goose by trying to keep it alive, right?

00:37:54.940 --> 00:37:55.740
Yeah.

00:37:55.740 --> 00:37:59.080
And to their credit, I have not actually talked to them about this.

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:17.860
It has been one of my concerns when I've talked to people about ideas about how we can, you know, sort of bring in some more money into PyPI in order to enable us to, you know, maybe hire more people to develop it or pay for some services where we weren't able to get donations, you know, things like that.

00:38:17.860 --> 00:38:25.860
And, you know, that's been sort of one of the big concerns there is how are these donors going to look at that.

00:38:25.860 --> 00:38:33.300
And, you know, we do try to, when we develop it, not depend too much on one specific donor.

00:38:33.300 --> 00:38:35.060
So we do try to spread out over multiple.

00:38:35.060 --> 00:38:39.860
We do try to develop things so that we're not developing just some sort of proprietary API.

00:38:39.860 --> 00:38:45.240
If we do, it's shimmed in in a way that we could, you know, swap in some other component.

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:47.220
So, you know, what do you think about this?

00:38:47.220 --> 00:38:56.180
Like, just listening to you guys talk, one of the ideas that was running through my mind is, Eric, I like your idea of having a private read the docs.

00:38:56.180 --> 00:39:03.420
One of the ideas on PyPI that was coming to mind is, well, what if you could have like a premium listing?

00:39:03.420 --> 00:39:07.420
So, like, I use Stripe and I pip install Stripe.

00:39:07.420 --> 00:39:09.780
And that comes down from there.

00:39:09.780 --> 00:39:12.580
But that's, you know, Stripe is a very successful business.

00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:16.000
I'm just grabbing an example of something I use that's for pay, basically, right?

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:30.920
What if Stripe could have like a premium listing on PyPI and all of the bandwidth and all the hosting charges for the premium listings were not passed through to like Rackspace and Fastly and stuff?

00:39:30.920 --> 00:39:32.160
That could be doable.

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:44.080
We'd have to essentially stand up almost a second PyPI to handle that just because there's no real way to discriminate between, you know, different packages where they go through.

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:48.700
I mean, the package files themselves could easily be hosted through another mechanism.

00:39:48.700 --> 00:39:59.460
But the repository API, the web UI, all that stuff would still have to actually go through, you know, Fastly and then Rackspace and the various companies.

00:39:59.460 --> 00:40:05.060
So it would be hard to completely separate them without making them two entirely separate entities.

00:40:05.060 --> 00:40:05.780
Okay.

00:40:05.780 --> 00:40:13.660
Carol, what are your thoughts on ways that we might be able to mix things up a bit here?

00:40:13.660 --> 00:40:17.700
Looking in from the outside, Eric and Donald are, you know, living this day to day, right?

00:40:17.700 --> 00:40:21.120
Yeah, I mean, I think it's one of those things.

00:40:21.120 --> 00:40:39.540
I think it's sort of a slippery slope, because if you did do the like sort of like extra like per company or whatever, PyPI, you kind of open the door for losing the huge benefit of PyPI, which is everybody sort of goes to the same place.

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:42.160
We've seen it in science and data science.

00:40:42.160 --> 00:40:50.360
There's some great stuff that came out of Conda and now more so Conda Forge along with PyPI.

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:56.080
But it also kind of increased the burden of, okay, how do we install things?

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:57.200
Do we use PIP?

00:40:57.200 --> 00:40:58.040
Do we use Conda?

00:40:58.460 --> 00:40:58.800
Yeah.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:04.300
I'm not sure that additional complexity is something that really benefits our users.

00:41:04.300 --> 00:41:07.100
Whereas, hey, this is where we go.

00:41:07.100 --> 00:41:07.700
Yeah.

00:41:07.700 --> 00:41:08.360
Easy decision.

00:41:08.360 --> 00:41:12.980
One of the things I wonder is if we couldn't use like pip.

00:41:13.220 --> 00:41:19.340
Donald's done such a great job of improving it with little readouts as your thing progresses.

00:41:19.900 --> 00:41:30.820
And even something as basic as, did you know, pip installs X number of terabytes of whatever data in a month or whatever, or whether that's on the PyPI site.

00:41:30.820 --> 00:41:37.860
But just building awareness, because I think it's going to be a combination of donations that you're going to get.

00:41:37.860 --> 00:41:49.800
You're going to get some individual donors that give to things like Read the Docs or PyPI or infrastructure because they see the value in it and they use it in their jobs every day.

00:41:49.800 --> 00:41:56.820
And it might not be what I develop every day, but I use it so much and I would hate to have it go away.

00:41:57.500 --> 00:42:05.480
So, you know, personally donating to the packaging and to Read the Docs for me was a no brainer.

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:08.640
But I'm in a position where I can do that.

00:42:08.640 --> 00:42:10.360
Not everybody can.

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:18.100
So, you know, we don't want to set up like a tiered structure to make people feel bad for giving what they can.

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:18.540
Yeah.

00:42:18.540 --> 00:42:19.580
And where they can.

00:42:19.580 --> 00:42:22.420
But I could see, well, a couple of things.

00:42:22.600 --> 00:42:42.300
One is Eva and the board and the greater PSF team has really worked hard the last year and a half to really level up the governance of PSF and to really look critically at what nonprofits are doing and how we can increase sustainability.

00:42:42.300 --> 00:42:55.920
And I think some of the first steps that got put in place was to make some strategic hires to support Eva and the sustainability in different areas of the foundation.

00:42:56.520 --> 00:43:07.780
And now it's really a matter of, okay, the next phase is really, okay, let's take a critical look at all of these things and come up with some best practices and plans.

00:43:07.780 --> 00:43:09.260
Just like we do in development.

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:17.160
Like, you know, we run things through continuous testing or integration and, you know, to work smarter, not harder.

00:43:17.160 --> 00:43:18.060
Yeah, exactly.

00:43:18.060 --> 00:43:29.020
Like leveraging, like you said, continuous deployment maybe to make sure that if something goes down, it's like a push button to create a new instance of it rather than a scramble for four days.

00:43:29.020 --> 00:43:30.420
Something like this, right?

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:30.960
Right.

00:43:30.960 --> 00:43:49.520
So my feeling is I would much prefer to see the big corporate companies that are really benefiting from Python somehow have a way to fund it but feel like they're getting something a lot out of it, right?

00:43:49.520 --> 00:44:08.040
Like that's kind of why I brought up the premium PyPI package where maybe like if you are a company and the PyPI package is about a thing that is really important to you, maybe somehow that listing could look different and they could pay for it but be really happy to do so, you know, or something similarly on read the docs.

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:19.500
I'm not really sure but I feel like the donations are great and I've given some money to PyPI but I don't feel like any amount of money that I can personally give is going to come anywhere near me.

00:44:19.500 --> 00:44:20.300
Near what?

00:44:20.300 --> 00:44:31.360
Microsoft, Red Hat, these other companies that have tons of money, Google, if they're making such big use of it and actually have a product on the other end.

00:44:31.360 --> 00:44:32.120
I don't know.

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:33.620
Eva, what do you think?

00:44:33.620 --> 00:44:41.160
So I sometimes find myself persuading people that open source needs money and that not everything can be handled by the community and volunteers.

00:44:41.160 --> 00:44:49.360
I even remember when I was hired, it was a taboo for me to get paid to work for the PSF.

00:44:49.360 --> 00:44:54.560
Because everyone was of the mindset that everything should be done by the community.

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:59.640
But I definitely agree that corporate sponsorship is where it's at.

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:05.980
And I feel that more corporations need to become aware of the fact that maintaining a software language has multiple angles.

00:45:05.980 --> 00:45:09.140
A lot of those angles require funding.

00:45:09.140 --> 00:45:13.860
Corporations that use Python should financially support Python in my opinion.

00:45:13.860 --> 00:45:19.880
And these companies are sometimes making millions and millions or billions of dollars on this stuff.

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:31.580
And if they cave 0.0001% of that revenue to the thing that their business is based on, it would transform it and be like nothing in their space, right?

00:45:31.580 --> 00:45:32.100
Exactly.

00:45:32.100 --> 00:45:41.120
And since Python is a core of what they do, I strongly believe that having good infrastructure behind the language is vital for the sustainability of that language.

00:45:41.120 --> 00:45:46.180
I mean, especially nowadays, there are so many options for programming languages.

00:45:46.180 --> 00:45:52.860
And we just have to increase the number of reasons we give our developers to stay in order to make Python sustainable for the long run.

00:45:52.860 --> 00:45:55.860
I mean, a little bit goes a long way.

00:45:55.860 --> 00:45:57.200
I totally agree with you, Eva.

00:45:57.200 --> 00:45:58.460
Eric, what do you think?

00:45:58.460 --> 00:46:01.280
100% behind a corporation's paying.

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:09.120
I mean, I think depending on Carol giving money to read the docs each month is very much similar to requiring her to pay us, right?

00:46:09.120 --> 00:46:12.160
Like, we would never require open source people to pay us.

00:46:12.160 --> 00:46:20.900
And asking that the people working on open source pay money to support the infrastructure while companies free ride, it just feels morally wrong to me.

00:46:20.900 --> 00:46:22.980
You know, Carol is contributing enough.

00:46:22.980 --> 00:46:24.880
She doesn't need to give us money.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:27.860
And people that are individuals do not need to give us money.

00:46:27.860 --> 00:46:35.660
And I've actually toyed with removing the ability to give individual donations from read the docs because I think it's a false flag.

00:46:35.660 --> 00:46:37.120
Like, it's never going to solve the problem.

00:46:37.120 --> 00:46:40.560
And the only people that are going to donate are already giving their time.

00:46:41.400 --> 00:46:45.380
And asking them to give money as well is just, it makes me sad.

00:46:45.380 --> 00:46:47.740
It does help, but it's like a small band-aid.

00:46:47.740 --> 00:46:50.640
It doesn't really solve the sustainability problem, right?

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:51.940
I think it distracts, right?

00:46:51.940 --> 00:46:52.180
Yeah.

00:46:52.180 --> 00:46:55.000
Like, people are like, oh, you just need to get more donations from individuals.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:56.840
And it's like, that's not the solution.

00:46:56.840 --> 00:46:59.620
Please stop suggesting that as the solution.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:02.560
And I'd be remiss not to mention a couple things here.

00:47:02.560 --> 00:47:10.180
So Nadia Eggbolt, I believe is her last name, did an amazing job for the Ford Foundation doing a report on this that's like 100 pages.

00:47:10.180 --> 00:47:12.200
And she talked a bunch about Python stuff.

00:47:12.200 --> 00:47:14.660
She talked to myself, Keith McGee, a bunch of other people.

00:47:14.660 --> 00:47:16.020
I think Donald as well, for sure.

00:47:16.400 --> 00:47:17.480
About these problems.

00:47:17.480 --> 00:47:21.340
And I think that is a very concrete report.

00:47:21.340 --> 00:47:25.060
And it really does talk about a lot of the different solutions that have been tried.

00:47:25.060 --> 00:47:32.780
I think especially with PyPI and kind of the pip example you cited, doing a kind of Wikipedia-style awareness campaign, right?

00:47:32.780 --> 00:47:37.780
So if you put in the pip install logs for a week, like, hey, donate to pip.

00:47:37.780 --> 00:47:38.840
This stuff is not free.

00:47:38.840 --> 00:47:39.700
We're run by a nonprofit.

00:47:39.700 --> 00:47:42.740
You know, very similar to how you see at the top of Wikipedia, right?

00:47:42.740 --> 00:47:46.620
Like, they really have to, like, push and be heard.

00:47:46.620 --> 00:47:51.580
And I think there's still a huge number of people that can kind of claim ignorance of this issue.

00:47:51.580 --> 00:48:05.420
And I think if you start putting that on every PyPI page or PyPI page, every read the docs page, every pip install, that would actually start to move the needle in terms of awareness and community, kind of galvanizing a community.

00:48:05.860 --> 00:48:14.920
And so I think something similar to what Ruby is doing with the Ruby Together efforts, where they're actually kind of they've taken their kind of core infrastructure.

00:48:14.920 --> 00:48:26.780
They've built some branding around improving it and then kind of showing results either kind of think monthly with those kind of people has been a really interesting thing.

00:48:27.120 --> 00:48:30.460
They're still nowhere near where they should be in terms of funding.

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:51.860
But I think if we kind of took, you know, PyPI, read the docs, even just those two, really, and, you know, in pip, even, for example, and we're like, hey, let's run a one week or a one month campaign, you know, maybe around PyCon, for example, or like, you know, the week up and after PyCon or something where it's like, hey, like, your infrastructure, you know, tie it with a keynote at PyCon U.S.

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:55.960
Tie it with, you know, these massive things where everyone during the sprints is going to see this.

00:48:55.960 --> 00:48:58.000
Everyone at their work is going to see this.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:07.920
You know, I think I think we've been very coy about this because it's something that we're kind of we feel awkward about money and open source has been this taboo subject for a long time.

00:49:07.920 --> 00:49:15.740
But I really do think that we're now at the point where we really have to kind of build sustainable solutions that bring the community in.

00:49:15.740 --> 00:49:24.800
And so I think that's kind of my my big picture idea is really that kind of I view read the docs at its core like a library, similar to the government stuff we were talking about earlier.

00:49:24.800 --> 00:49:24.980
Right.

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:36.900
We should be funded by taxpayers, you know, and if we're not able to, you know, one of the other things I thought about is going to VCs and doing, you know, a 1% for open source or something along those lines.

00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:43.560
You know, I think the things that the green movement and kind of the environmental people are dealing with are very similar.

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:43.860
Right.

00:49:43.860 --> 00:49:46.320
Where there are these externalities that people don't feel.

00:49:46.320 --> 00:49:50.060
It's a really interesting angle to think of it as this is an externality.

00:49:50.060 --> 00:49:50.840
Right.

00:49:50.840 --> 00:49:58.860
This is an expense that people that use open source don't have to pay because it's somehow covered.

00:49:58.860 --> 00:50:05.340
And basically, a lot of it is pushed on to the companies that donate like Rackspace and Fastly.

00:50:05.340 --> 00:50:06.000
Right.

00:50:06.060 --> 00:50:07.400
They're covering the cost of all this.

00:50:07.400 --> 00:50:11.420
So all the other companies in the world can go make money and not worry about it.

00:50:11.420 --> 00:50:12.140
Right.

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:12.480
Right.

00:50:12.480 --> 00:50:17.380
Like open source contributors burning out is the global warming of the technology industry.

00:50:17.380 --> 00:50:17.660
Right.

00:50:17.660 --> 00:50:18.020
Right.

00:50:18.020 --> 00:50:28.460
Because I think there's something really special about the volunteer effort and how people are putting forward all this effort for nothing but to bring some project to fruition.

00:50:28.780 --> 00:50:45.020
But at the same time, when you see billions of dollars being made by for profit companies on top of this infrastructure and on top of this, these projects, it seems like there's got to be a way that they're not crushing the people trying to do the work, you know, with their weight.

