00:52:16.720 --> 00:52:22.920
you'll see, you know, typically you'll see, you'll see, you'll see, you'll see, pip install, you know, my whole library for that company.

00:52:22.920 --> 00:52:30.120
So, you know, those companies do tend to drive a lot of traffic towards PyPI, which, you know, increases our costs.

00:52:30.120 --> 00:52:31.840
And they sort of get that for free.

00:52:31.840 --> 00:52:40.880
Now, we're happy to provide that for free, but, you know, they do impact our bottom line to a large degree.

00:52:41.720 --> 00:52:47.700
I really think that the best sort of end case is for these companies to give back.

00:52:47.700 --> 00:52:56.720
You know, I worry about, like, the Wikipedia style, the donation drive and such, in that we're going to end up just getting money from developers.

00:52:56.720 --> 00:53:02.160
Again, someone who goes to PyPI online is likely going to be a developer looking for a library.

00:53:02.160 --> 00:53:06.440
Someone who takes pip install on their command line is likely to be a developer.

00:53:06.720 --> 00:53:12.400
You know, and the hope there, I guess, is that they will funnel that up towards their management chains.

00:53:12.400 --> 00:53:14.240
Say, hey, we depend on this thing.

00:53:14.240 --> 00:53:15.180
Can we give it money?

00:53:15.180 --> 00:53:22.040
But I worry that the most likely case is that they will maybe give some money themselves and it just kind of ends there.

00:53:22.800 --> 00:53:28.200
I'm not necessarily sort of super skilled at the donation side of things.

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:32.040
You know, I reach out to companies and beg them for services.

00:53:32.040 --> 00:53:44.000
But, you know, I feel like identifying which companies are big Python users and then reaching out to them and asking them for donations is probably going to be our best bet.

00:53:44.460 --> 00:53:51.800
And in many ways, PyPI is lucky because we do have the, you know, we're owned by the PSF.

00:53:51.800 --> 00:53:55.860
So there's already, you know, a infrastructure set up to get donations.

00:53:55.860 --> 00:54:02.040
And, you know, we're likely, as far as PyPI is concerned, best of trying to improve upon that.

00:54:02.480 --> 00:54:10.480
I think that there is actually a path forward where everybody wins, where Python open source infrastructure is funded and supported better.

00:54:10.480 --> 00:54:15.960
It's not all the eggs in one basket, even though thank you, thank you, Rackspace and Fastly and so on.

00:54:15.960 --> 00:54:23.860
And these companies, like you said, the biggest ones that drive the most traffic, they feel like somehow some change has been made.

00:54:23.860 --> 00:54:25.340
So they actually get better visibility.

00:54:25.340 --> 00:54:26.100
They get better.

00:54:26.100 --> 00:54:33.480
Their thing that they have a Python library for is doing better with Python developers because of it.

00:54:33.480 --> 00:54:34.640
I don't know.

00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:36.860
I just, the ad model may work somehow.

00:54:36.860 --> 00:54:47.520
The donation model, while really appreciated, I know, is it's not really enough to sustain, like, a person working all the time or, like, you know, the cost of a lot of times.

00:54:47.520 --> 00:54:49.720
It feels more like there's the yearly drive.

00:54:50.340 --> 00:54:55.640
So, you know, we're kind of getting near the end of our time, but do we have a solution?

00:54:55.640 --> 00:54:59.560
I'm not sure we found any solutions, but I feel like we've started an interesting discussion.

00:54:59.560 --> 00:55:04.100
Eva, what's the PFS story here?

00:55:04.100 --> 00:55:05.820
Like, what do you think?

00:55:05.820 --> 00:55:15.000
For the PSF, I definitely have short-term goals, which I guess is the best solution I can come up with at this time.

00:55:15.120 --> 00:55:21.020
I mean, we've been talking about trying to maybe get traffic statistics that are more targeted.

00:55:21.020 --> 00:55:24.520
Say, hey, this is how your team's using this infrastructure.

00:55:24.520 --> 00:55:39.860
And I'm not quite sure if anything beyond them benefiting from it should be a part of the reward for sponsorship because they're already getting a lot from just using it for free.

00:55:40.460 --> 00:55:48.960
So maybe that's just it, just showing them this is how exactly your team is benefiting from Python and the infrastructure.

00:55:48.960 --> 00:55:51.340
It would be great if you can give back.

00:55:51.340 --> 00:55:56.700
I mean, it's not like every sponsor has to give us $30,000, $50,000 a year.

00:55:57.080 --> 00:56:08.140
If all corporate sponsors that use Python give a little every year, I think that could add up to hiring two developers.

00:56:08.140 --> 00:56:22.640
I mean, within the PSF, I want to have an environment where my staff, my team is not worried about how long is my job here for because it's pending on some kind of funding.

00:56:22.640 --> 00:56:26.680
I want to make sure that I can pay someone at least five years before I hire them.

00:56:26.680 --> 00:56:28.900
So just taking steps like that.

00:56:28.900 --> 00:56:29.300
Okay.

00:56:29.300 --> 00:56:29.500
Yeah.

00:56:29.500 --> 00:56:32.080
I think on one hand, you know, it is a big problem.

00:56:32.080 --> 00:56:37.900
But on the other, like you said, Eva, it's just if people, people, by people, I mean companies.

00:56:38.700 --> 00:56:42.540
If companies gave a little, it would solve it straight away, right?

00:56:42.540 --> 00:56:55.740
I still feel like having some kind of business model that is doesn't seem incongruent with open source and the whole story, but does does bring in a little bit of stability would be a good thing.

00:56:55.740 --> 00:57:00.840
Carol, what do you think coming from like a Jupyter scientific person perspective?

00:57:01.340 --> 00:57:02.840
I've got two major thoughts.

00:57:02.840 --> 00:57:07.660
One is I would highly encourage folks in the Jupyter data science world.

00:57:07.660 --> 00:57:22.540
If you're looking for a great project to do analytics on, approach us because there may be a project that you can look at to analyze the traffic data and, you know, see who's using it, who's consuming it.

00:57:22.540 --> 00:57:27.520
And really help us out with the analytics side of things and the reporting side of things.

00:57:27.520 --> 00:57:37.080
And then the other thing I think is I had the pleasure of attending an open source sustainability thing with Nadia Agbel earlier this year that O'Reilly put on.

00:57:37.080 --> 00:57:42.480
And she and I come from both business background as well as nonprofit.

00:57:42.480 --> 00:57:55.260
And I think Eric kind of hit on one group of donors that benefit a lot from open source yet don't directly donate a whole lot to it.

00:57:55.260 --> 00:57:56.860
And that is the venture capitalists.

00:57:56.860 --> 00:58:08.260
And if you took the top 20 venture capitalists and they donated 10, 25,000 to sustain the community, it would go a long way.

00:58:08.260 --> 00:58:25.640
And I think that may be another area that we look a little closer at and say, okay, you're funding hackathons and giving money away to potentially promising companies down the road that may or may not make it out of their first year of life.

00:58:25.640 --> 00:58:32.020
But we know that the Python Foundation has been around for a long time.

00:58:32.200 --> 00:58:41.840
We know that Python's been around for a long time and perhaps go back to them and say, hey, you need to support the infrastructure that you are directly benefiting from.

00:58:41.840 --> 00:58:43.180
Yeah, that's an interesting point.

00:58:43.180 --> 00:58:44.840
And VCs were on my mind as well.

00:58:44.840 --> 00:58:46.500
And these high growth companies.

00:58:46.500 --> 00:58:58.220
One of the things that came to mind when you were saying this, what if there was some kind of PSF funded or officially funded expert, a group of experts that could come in?

00:58:58.260 --> 00:59:02.240
So instead of just going to the VCs saying, look, you have these startups and these accelerators.

00:59:02.240 --> 00:59:05.840
And because you benefit from this, you should donate to us.

00:59:05.840 --> 00:59:14.980
But because you benefit from us, if you donate to us, we'll actually help your companies get started by giving you 10 hours a week of expert advice.

00:59:14.980 --> 00:59:20.020
And obviously, that would have to more than cover that expert's time and energy and so on.

00:59:20.020 --> 00:59:21.380
But maybe there's some kind of partnership.

00:59:21.380 --> 00:59:22.240
Who knows?

00:59:22.240 --> 00:59:23.840
Donald, final thought.

00:59:23.840 --> 00:59:25.000
Where do we go from here?

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:35.040
I think right now, PyPI is a relatively okay place as far as our hosting infrastructure goes.

00:59:35.040 --> 00:59:41.380
Our donors have been fairly stable and we've done a pretty good job at diversifying them.

00:59:41.380 --> 00:59:45.960
It is always scary that one of them could drop out and how we would handle that.

00:59:46.920 --> 00:59:57.560
Looking forward, I do think that the best way to look at this is how to get your corporations, VCs, etc., to sort of contribute back.

00:59:57.560 --> 01:00:01.860
And that's kind of where I'm at.

01:00:01.860 --> 01:00:02.240
Okay.

01:00:02.240 --> 01:00:05.680
Good to hear PyPI is not just about to vanish or anything.

01:00:05.860 --> 01:00:12.400
But still, it needs a much more stable base, I think, given its vast importance.

01:00:12.400 --> 01:00:13.980
Eric, final thoughts?

01:00:13.980 --> 01:00:16.200
I think the last thing I said were probably my final thoughts.

01:00:16.200 --> 01:00:17.300
All right.

01:00:17.300 --> 01:00:17.560
Great.

01:00:17.560 --> 01:00:22.880
I mean, I think, yeah, I'm obviously very much, you know, I think I have personal stake in this.

01:00:23.120 --> 01:00:30.620
And, you know, I think everyone else here is paid, you know, or until recently has been paid full time in some fashion to work on this.

01:00:30.620 --> 01:00:34.660
Whereas I have been watching my bank account dwindle trying to solve this problem.

01:00:34.660 --> 01:00:36.960
And so I think that's why it's a little bit more personal for me.

01:00:36.960 --> 01:00:37.540
Yeah, absolutely.

01:00:37.540 --> 01:00:40.360
And why I have a little bit of, you know, passion, maybe.

01:00:40.360 --> 01:00:43.060
Well, you had some really interesting points.

01:00:43.060 --> 01:00:46.940
And, you know, I can definitely share some thoughts with you.

01:00:46.940 --> 01:00:56.920
Like, in February, I went full time on having just my podcast be my 100% income and the training courses that I built on top of it.

01:00:56.920 --> 01:01:06.880
And it's not open source exactly, but it's, you know, it's working in the open source community to, you know, pay my kids' school bills and mortgage and stuff.

01:01:06.880 --> 01:01:07.800
And it's stressful.

01:01:07.800 --> 01:01:13.160
And I don't have exactly the same constraints because I kind of live alongside open source, right?

01:01:13.160 --> 01:01:14.460
Like, I can do ads.

01:01:14.460 --> 01:01:18.740
And people, I think, understand for the most part, like, this is paying my bills.

01:01:18.740 --> 01:01:19.860
So it's okay.

01:01:19.860 --> 01:01:21.100
We'll listen to a 30-second ad.

01:01:21.100 --> 01:01:23.340
But it's a challenge, right?

01:01:23.340 --> 01:01:24.200
Yeah, definitely.

01:01:24.200 --> 01:01:30.260
And I think the biggest thing for me is that, you know, four years ago, this felt like nobody was talking about this.

01:01:30.260 --> 01:01:33.360
And I really do think that the awareness has just slowly been raised.

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:37.960
Because the work that Nadia did was monumental and just kind of the fact we're doing a podcast about it.

01:01:37.960 --> 01:01:42.940
And I really think it is more, you know, it's one of those things where we just really do need to keep building awareness.

01:01:42.940 --> 01:01:44.780
Because everyone I talked to was like, oh, read the docs.

01:01:44.780 --> 01:01:46.260
I thought that was like a VC-backed company.

01:01:46.260 --> 01:01:47.900
Or, you know, it's like we thought.

01:01:47.900 --> 01:01:49.540
That's an Eric-backed company.

01:01:49.540 --> 01:01:50.840
Exactly, right?

01:01:50.840 --> 01:01:58.100
But I think I haven't personally done a great job of raising that awareness and been very skittish about introducing money into this ecosystem.

01:01:58.100 --> 01:02:01.000
But I mean, I think at the end of the day, especially for infrastructure, right?

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:05.760
Like, people will happily work on cool new features, like, for fun.

01:02:05.760 --> 01:02:09.480
But, like, paying someone to wear a pager is something you have to do.

01:02:09.480 --> 01:02:11.020
Like, nobody wants to sign up.

01:02:11.020 --> 01:02:17.960
And I would feel bad making somebody sign up for free to wear a pager and get woken up at three in the morning to provide a service for free to corporations.

01:02:18.600 --> 01:02:24.120
You know, like, that's just not something that I feel good about in any aspect of it.

01:02:24.120 --> 01:02:28.720
And so I think there is a fundamental need of money for a subset of these efforts.

01:02:28.720 --> 01:02:31.000
And I think the community is coming around to that.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:32.940
I think the conversations are happening.

01:02:32.940 --> 01:02:36.560
And I think we're really in a very positive forward path.

01:02:36.560 --> 01:02:38.160
And we just need to keep doing it.

01:02:38.160 --> 01:02:38.680
All right.

01:02:38.680 --> 01:02:43.600
Well, I hope that we can somehow bring this up in PyCon this year in June.

01:02:43.600 --> 01:02:49.040
And maybe some lightning talks, maybe a keynote, hint, hint, hint, nudge, nudge, or some open spaces or something.

01:02:49.040 --> 01:02:51.680
But I think it's great these conversations are happening.

01:02:51.680 --> 01:02:53.660
And thank you all for being here.

01:02:53.660 --> 01:03:01.160
It was really interesting to brainstorm about what we can do, what the problems are, and what the solutions might be.

